The grammar contains lexical rules for every terminal that appears in the string.  
A convenient way to derive the sentence is to start with the production  

S → NT28 NT64  

and let  

NT64 ⇒ 't80'                           (covers the last symbol)  

while NT28 generates the first 27 symbols by repeatedly using the left-recursive rule  

NT28 → NT28 NT31  

to create an arbitrarily long left segment, finally expanding each non-terminal on the fringe to the required terminals:

NT28 ⇒ NT22 NT39 …  
NT22 ⇒ 't143'  
NT39 ⇒ NT8 NT35 …  
NT8  ⇒ 't25'  
NT35 ⇒ 't68'  
⋯ (continue similarly, using the available lexical rules  
     NT59 ⇒ 't111', NT22 ⇒ 't2', NT14 ⇒ 't47', NT61 ⇒ 't147',  
     NT9  ⇒ 't174', NT21 ⇒ 't23', NT50 ⇒ 't76', NT49 ⇒ 't59',  
     NT19 ⇒ 't64', NT60 ⇒ 't103', NT61 ⇒ 't33', NT59 ⇒ 't153',  
     NT42 ⇒ 't85', NT25 ⇒ 't176', NT11 ⇒ 't48', NT27 ⇒ 't51',  
     NT63 ⇒ 't13', NT60 ⇒ 't103', NT70 ⇒ 't170', NT39 ⇒ 't17',  
     NT22 ⇒ 't45', NT21 ⇒ 't56', NT59 ⇒ 't153', NT23 ⇒ 't19').

Because every needed lexical production exists and the recursive rules (NT28 → NT28 NT31, NT31 → NT31 NT24, etc.) allow us to concatenate them in any desired order, the entire 28-token string can be generated.

Yes

For the given string, the first terminal symbol is t71.  
In this grammar t71 is produced only by the non-terminal NT25 through the rule  

  NT25 → 't71'  

To be in the language, the left component of the start rule S → A B must eventually be able to generate NT25 as its very first (left-most) terminal.  
The only possibilities for A are the six non-terminals that appear on the left side of the start rules:

 • NT60 (S → NT60 NT67)  
 • NT47 (S → NT47 NT44)  
 • NT63 (S → NT63 NT58)  
 • NT49 (S → NT49 NT3)  
 • NT28 (S → NT28 NT64)  
 • NT38 (S → NT38 NT62)

Examining every production for these six symbols:

• None of them has a direct lexical rule that yields t71.  
• None of them has a rule whose leftmost child can ultimately reduce to NT25.  
  (The only rule that mentions NT25 on a right-hand side is NT47 → NT0 NT25, but the first
  symbol generated there is NT0, and NT0 can only generate the lexical t24 as its first
  terminal, never t71.)

Hence, no derivation starting from S can have t71 as the first output symbol, so the
given string cannot be produced by the grammar.

No

The start symbol S can only expand in one step as follows  

1. S → NT60 NT58  
2. S → NT47 NT44  
3. S → NT63 NT58  
4. S → NT49 NT3  
5. S → NT28 NT64  
6. S → NT38 NT62  

Whatever production is chosen, the very first token of the generated string is the first token produced by the left-hand constituent of that production (NT60, NT47, NT63, NT49, NT28, or NT38).  
So, to match the given string the first token these non-terminals can ultimately emit must be t71.

Looking at all lexical (terminal) rules in the grammar we find that the only non-terminal that can generate t71 directly is  

NT25 → 't71'  

No other non-terminal has a lexical rule for t71.

Therefore, to have t71 as the first token, the left constituent of S must eventually derive NT25 as its leftmost leaf.  
Checking every occurrence of NT25 in binary rules shows that it only ever appears as the SECOND symbol on a right-hand side (e.g. NT47 → NT0 NT25, NT34 → NT36 NT25, NT35 → NT10 NT25, …).  
Consequently, whenever NT25 is used, some other token necessarily precedes the t71 it produces.

Hence none of NT60, NT47, NT63, NT49, NT28, or NT38 can generate a string whose very first token is t71.  
Since the given string begins with t71, it cannot be derived from S.

Thus the string is not in the language generated by the grammar.

No

The only start-rule that can place the token t97 at the beginning of the string is

 S → NT60 NT67  (NT60 → 't97')

Hence NT67 would have to derive the remaining 13 tokens  

t170  t148  t47  t1  t111  t90  t76  t126  t64  t96  t85  t96  t68.

NT67 can expand only by the seven binary rules

 NT67 → NT53 NT36  
 NT67 → NT32 NT67  
 NT67 → NT0  NT53  
 NT67 → NT49 NT35  
 NT67 → NT33 NT43  
 NT67 → NT26 NT70  
 NT67 → NT20 NT41.

Because the last symbol in the required suffix is t68 (generated only by NT35 → 't68'), the only viable expansion for the outermost NT67 is

 NT67 → NT49 NT35  (NT35 → 't68').

Thus NT49 would have to generate the twelve-token substring

 t170  t148  t47  t1  t111  t90  t76  t126  t64  t96  t85  t96.

NT49, however, has just four possible productions:

 NT49 → 't59'  
 NT49 → NT62 NT44  
 NT49 → NT70 NT11  
 NT49 → NT63 NT50.

The first, second and fourth alternatives are impossible, because they can yield at most two terminals and none of them can start with t170.  
Therefore we must use

 NT49 → NT70 NT11  (NT70 → 't170').

This leaves NT11 to derive the eleven-token tail

 t148  t47  t1  t111  t90  t76  t126  t64  t96  t85  t96.

But NT11 has only the following options:

 NT11 → NT52 NT39  
 NT11 → NT58 NT38  
 NT11 → NT71 NT13  
 NT11 → NT60 NT17  
 NT11 → 't48'.

None of these can produce a string that contains no occurrence of t145, t17 or t158 (the only terminals NT39 can produce) and yet contains both t85 (which requires NT42) and two occurrences of t96 (which require NT70).  Consequently NT11 cannot derive the required eleven-token substring, so NT49 cannot generate the twelve-token substring, and NT67 cannot generate the thirteen-token suffix.

Therefore the given grammar cannot produce the entire fourteen-token string.

No

The first symbol of the string is t103.  
In the grammar the only non-terminal that can directly generate t103 is NT60 (rule NT60 -> 't103').  

Looking at the six productions for S:

S -> NT60 NT58  
S -> NT47 NT44  
S -> NT63 NT58  
S -> NT49 NT3  
S -> NT28 NT64  
S -> NT38 NT62  

the only way to begin a derivation with t103 is to use the first rule  
S → NT60 NT58.

Hence the remainder of the string (the 18 tokens starting with t90) would need to be generated by NT58.

But NT58 can only expand through the following patterns:

NT58 → NT46 NT21  
NT58 → NT31 NT14  
NT58 → NT62 NT10  
NT58 → NT58 NT39

In each case, the very first terminal produced comes from the first non-terminal on the right-hand side (NT46, NT31, NT62, or a recursively generated NT58).  
None of these non-terminals (NT46, NT31, NT62, NT58) can ultimately produce the terminal t90 as their left-most symbol: their possible left-most terminals are limited to {t167, t77, t89, t60, t47, t126, t109, t115, t79, t88, t148, t80, t23, t75, …}, none of which is t90.

Consequently, NT58 cannot derive a string whose first symbol is t90.  
Therefore the grammar cannot produce the given string, and the string is not in the language.
